			<div class="content" id="post-content-2468950">
									

<blockquote>
<p>One minor thing that could be done would be to break up the paragraphs more when you want to get across a sense of a faster pace. Good for action. It's a cheap little technique, but it might help a little.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That's an interesting point, and instead I see that have done nearly the opposite of that, where the more uneventful parts are short paragraphs and the engagements are long and detailed. Partially this is because the purpose of these things is to inform future training and procedures, and so the detail focus on where it isn't a controlled situation and lessons can be learned is needed. Also though I think I was perhaps subconsciously relating the way that time <em>feels</em> when things become &quot;kinetic&quot;, seconds stretch out and certain details become hyper-emphasized in your memory. I am not sure if splitting up the kinetic paragraphs more wouldn't have an effect that is opposite to putting the reader into the action, actually.</p>

							</div>

								
					
